### Sporting event delegation

### Panama at the [2015 Pan American Games](/2015_Pan_American_Games)

This is about Panama's participation in the [2015 Pan American Games](/2015_Pan_American_Games), a rather significant regional sporting event, held in the sprawling metropolis of [Toronto](/Toronto), Canada. The games themselves spanned from July 10th to July 26th, 2015, a period that, for the athletes involved, felt like an eternity of sweat and strained muscles, punctuated by fleeting moments of triumph or crushing disappointment. Panama, represented by its national Olympic Committee, the [Comité Olímpico de Panamá](/Comit%C3%A9_Ol%C3%ADmpico_de_Panam%C3%A1) (identified by the [IOC code](/List_of_IOC_country_codes) PAN), sent a contingent of 44 competitors. These athletes, a mix of seasoned veterans and eager newcomers, were slated to compete across 12 distinct sports. It's a curious detail, isn't it? The sheer variety of human endeavor compressed into a single event. The [opening ceremony](/2015_Pan_American_Games_national_flag_bearers), a spectacle of national pride and synchronized movement, saw swimmer [Édgar Crespo](/%C3%89dgar_Crespo) proudly carry the Panamanian flag, a symbol of their nation’s aspirations on the international stage. Later, at the [closing ceremony](/2015_Pan_American_Games_closing_ceremony), the honor fell to [Eileen Grench](/Eileen_Grench), a testament to the diverse talents that represented Panama. The ultimate scorecard, the [medals](/2015_Pan_American_Games_medal_table), placed Panama in a rather unremarkable 24th position overall. A meager haul of two medals: one silver, one bronze. Not exactly a dynasty in the making, but then again, the pursuit of excellence is rarely a straightforward path. This marked another chapter in Panama's long history of participation in the Pan American Games, a lineage stretching back to [1951](/Panama_at_the_1951_Pan_American_Games) and continuing through a consistent presence in subsequent editions, including [1955](/Panama_at_the_1955_Pan_American_Games), [1959](/Panama_at_the_1959_Pan_American_Games), [1963](/Panama_at_the_1963_Pan_American_Games), [1967](/Panama_at_the_1967_Pan_American_Games), [1971](/Panama_at_the_1971_Pan_American_Games), [1975](/Panama_at_the_1975_Pan_American_Games), [1979](/Panama_at_the_1979_Pan_American_Games), [1983](/Panama_at_the_1983_Pan_American_Games), [1987](/Panama_at_the_1987_Pan_American_Games), [1991](/Panama_at_the_1991_Pan_American_Games), [1995](/Panama_at_the_1995_Pan_American_Games), [1999](/Panama_at_the_1999_Pan_American_Games), [2003](/Panama_at_the_2003_Pan_American_Games), [2007](/Panama_at_the_2007_Pan_American_Games), [2011](/Panama_at_the_2011_Pan_American_Games), and then this one in 2015, followed by [2019](/Panama_at_the_2019_Pan_American_Games) and [2023](/Panama_at_the_2023_Pan_American_Games). A consistent, if not always spectacular, presence.

[Panama](/Panama) indeed sent its athletes to compete in the [2015 Pan American Games](/2015_Pan_American_Games), a quadrennial celebration of athletic prowess held in the vibrant city of [Toronto](/Toronto), Canada. The games officially commenced on July 10th and concluded on July 26th, 2015. The nation's delegation, comprising 44 individuals, was set to showcase their skills across 12 different sporting disciplines. This representation was overseen by the [Comité Olímpico de Panamá](/Comit%C3%A9_Ol%C3%ADmpico_de_Panamá), the official National Olympic Committee recognized under the [IOC code](/List_of_IOC_country_codes) PAN. The symbolic mantle of [flag bearer (opening)](/2015_Pan_American_Games_national_flag_bearers) was entrusted to the swimmer [Édgar Crespo](/%C3%89dgar_Crespo), a choice that likely resonated with the nation's aquatic hopefuls. As the games drew to a close, the honor of carrying the flag at the [flag bearer (closing)](/2015_Pan_American_Games_closing_ceremony) fell to [Eileen Grench](/Eileen_Grench). The final tally, reflected in the [medals](/2015_Pan_American_Games_medal_table), saw Panama positioned at 24th place, having secured a total of two medals: one silver and one bronze. This participation extended Panama's continuous engagement with the Pan American Games, a tradition that began in [1951](/Panama_at_the_1951_Pan_American_Games) and has seen them present at every subsequent edition, including [1955](/Panama_at_the_1955_Pan_American_Games), [1959](/Panama_at_the_1959_Pan_American_Games), [1963](/Panama_at_the_1963_Pan_American_Games), [1967](/Panama_at_the_1967_Pan_American_Games), [1971](/Panama_at_the_1971_Pan_American_Games), [1975](/Panama_at_the_1975_Pan_American_Games), [1979](/Panama_at_the_1979_Pan_American_Games), [1983](/Panama_at_the_1983_Pan_American_Games), [1987](/Panama_at_the_1987_Pan_American_Games), [1991](/Panama_at_the_1991_Pan_American_Games), [1995](/Panama_at_the_1995_Pan_American_Games), [1999](/Panama_at_the_1999_Pan_American_Games), [2003](/Panama_at_the_2003_Pan_American_Games), [2007](/Panama_at_the_2007_Pan_American_Games), [2011](/Panama_at_the_2011_Pan_American_Games), and continuing on to [2019](/Panama_at_the_2019_Pan_American_Games) and [2023](/Panama_at_the_2023_Pan_American_Games).

